{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1ef8743b-da94-4eb7-ab89-958dc8b18e86","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, so there's no project to inspect. Here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Makes it installable via: dotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- Must be Exe for a tool -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for …</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</RepositoryUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n| Property | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool=true` | Tells `dotnet pack` to produce a tool package |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users will invoke |\n| `OutputType=Exe` | Required — tools must be executables |\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # stdio transport, ready for MCP clients\n```\n\nThat's the minimal setup. Want me to scaffold the project or create the `.csproj` file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"21a3f9d3-84bd-448b-af9b-142fc7b03e12","outputTokens":519},"id":"c91e3426-9bad-412c-9c78-6f3ee329e298","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:43:29.419Z","parentId":"683ca10c-ee00-492f-8b86-16030541ffe1"}
